"""
MKT Context Commentary — Judges chapters 14–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-14-17.py

Ch14: Samson's Timnite marriage — cross-cultural marriage negotiation, riddle contest,
      wedding feast customs, Philistine city geography (84 verses across 4 chs)
Ch15: Foxes/torches agricultural warfare, jawbone combat, water from rock
Ch16: Gaza gate, Delilah bribe, Nazirite vow, temple of Dagon archaeology
Ch17: Micah's shrine — ephod/teraphim, the landless Levite, the refrain

Key decisions:
- Dagon identified as the Philistine grain deity with Ugaritic background
- Tel Qasile pillared-temple archaeology cited for ch16 temple structure
- Honor-shame framework used throughout for revenge/vow dynamics
- Nazirite vow background from Num 6 applied to ch16:17
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "14": {
    "1": "<p><strong>Timnah</strong> (modern Khirbet Tibnah) lay in the Sorek Valley about 8 km northwest of Samson's hometown of Zorah, on the boundary between Israelite-held hills and Philistine-controlled lowlands. The Sorek Valley was a natural corridor from the coastal plain into the Shephelah — geographically, economically, and ethnically a contested frontier zone. Samson's downward movement (<em>wayyēred</em>, he went down) is both geographical (from Zorah's hills to the valley) and narratively ominous: every Samson episode involving a woman involves descent.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ancient Israelite marriage was arranged through the father, who negotiated the <em>môhar</em> (bride-price) and entered a binding covenant with the bride's family. Requesting a foreign wife violated both the cultural expectation of endogamy (marriage within the clan or tribe) and the specific Deuteronomic prohibition against covenanting with the Canaanite peoples (Deut 7:1-4). While Philistines were not technically Canaanites, the principle of separation applied. Samson bypasses normal protocol by reporting the request himself rather than sending his father to negotiate — itself a social irregularity.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>'Uncircumcised Philistines'</strong> (<em>ʾarlê pĕlištîm</em>) — circumcision was the physical covenant-marker distinguishing Israel from surrounding nations. The Philistines were the paradigmatic uncircumcised people in the Hebrew Bible (1 Sam 17:26, 36; 2 Sam 1:20), and the phrase became a term of contempt. The Philistines arrived as Sea Peoples from the Aegean around 1200 BCE and did not practice circumcision, unlike most Semitic neighbors. His father and mother's question appeals to both covenant logic (don't mix with those who bear no covenant sign) and practical wisdom (available women within the extended family).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The narrator's explanatory comment — <strong>'this was from the LORD, who was seeking an occasion against the Philistines'</strong> — addresses a theological problem that ancient readers would have noticed: how can YHWH use Samson's sinful desire for a foreign woman? The ANE background is the concept of divine hardening used throughout the Hebrew Bible (Exod 4:21; 1 Sam 2:25; 1 Kgs 22:22) — YHWH works within and through human choices, even sinful ones, to accomplish sovereign purposes. This does not exculpate Samson; it places his narrative within the larger framework of YHWH's war against Philistine oppression.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The route to Timnah passed through the <strong>vineyards of Timnah</strong> — the Sorek Valley was wine-producing territory (the name Sorek means 'choice grapevine'). A vineyard attack by a young lion (<em>kĕpîr ʾărāyôt</em>, a mature young lion capable of independent hunting) was a real danger in the ancient Levant; lions inhabited the Jordan River basin and surrounding terrain well into the monarchic period and later. Samson's separation from his parents for the encounter preserves the secret: he tells neither parent what he has done (v.6,9).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Killing a lion barehanded was the paradigmatic act of heroic valor in ANE warrior culture. Heracles was depicted killing the Nemean lion; David claims lion-killing as his qualification for facing Goliath (1 Sam 17:34-36); Benaiah son of Jehoiada is celebrated for killing a lion in a pit on a snowy day (2 Sam 23:20). The Spirit of YHWH rushing upon Samson (<em>wattillaḥ ʿālāyw rûaḥ YHWH</em>) is the same empowerment formula used at Othniel (3:10), Gideon (6:34), and Jephthah (11:29) — but here it enables a feat of raw physical strength rather than military leadership. Samson's silence about it shows he is not performing for honor, at least in this instance.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samson's conversation with the woman (<em>wayyiḏabber ʿim-hāʾiššāh</em>) follows the betrothal negotiation. The phrase <em>wayyîšar Šimšôn bĕʿênāyw</em> (she pleased Samson, literally 'she was right/straight in his eyes') uses the same root as the Judges refrain 'everyone did what was right in his own eyes' (<em>hayyāšār bĕʿênāyw</em>): what Samson finds straight and right is determined by personal desire, the book's definition of the problem.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The return to Timnah to complete the marriage is accompanied by the curiosity of checking the dead lion's carcass. The time gap ('after some time') suggests weeks or months. Contact with a dead body (<em>nepeš mēt</em>) was ritually polluting for all Israelites (Num 19:11-16) and doubly prohibited for Nazirites (Num 6:6-7: 'he shall not approach a dead body'). The honeybees settling in a lion's carcass is an unusual but not impossible event — bees occasionally colonize protected hollow spaces including dry cavities. Samson scoops the honey with his hands, both touching the carcass and potentially consuming something from an unclean source.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Samson brings the honey to his parents without disclosing its source — the narrator's emphasis on their eating it without knowing (<em>wĕhēmmāh lōʾ yādĕʿû</em>) implicates them in the defilement. The honey episode sets up the riddle: only someone who knew the specific source could solve it. In ANE wisdom tradition, an impossible riddle — one requiring inside knowledge — was a legitimate intellectual challenge but also a form of deception when used in a wager. Samson's riddle is designed to be unsolvable from the outside.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>The wedding feast</strong> (<em>mišteh</em>, H4960 — a drinking-feast, from <em>šātāh</em>, to drink) was a standard ANE institution lasting seven days for a principal wedding. Jacob served a week-long feast at his marriage to Leah (Gen 29:27-28). The feast was hosted at the bride's location (the bride's family's responsibility in Philistine custom here), with the bridegroom and his party as guests. The logistics involved significant hospitality expense — feeding and entertaining a large party for a week was a matter of community honor.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Philistines provide <strong>thirty companions</strong> (<em>šĕlōšîm mērēʿîm</em>) for Samson. In some ANE wedding contexts, groomsmen were provided by the host community to honor the guest and also to keep watch over a potentially dangerous visitor. Samson's superhuman reputation may have been known — the 30 men serve as both honor-guard and surveillance. This number will become the stake in the riddle wager and then the source of Samson's murderous retaliation in v.19.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Riddle contests at feasts were a recognized feature of ANE symposium culture, attested in Egyptian and Ugaritic texts. A successful riddler demonstrated superior intelligence and access to hidden knowledge. The <strong>wager</strong> — 30 linen garments and 30 changes of clothing — represented significant wealth: fine linen was an expensive import, and 60 items of clothing was a substantial wardrobe by ancient standards. The seven-day time limit matches the feast's duration, making the contest a formal feature of the wedding entertainment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The counter-wager is exactly symmetrical — 30 garments each way. The balance of the wager is a matter of honor: neither side can appear to be gambling unfairly. The public nature of the challenge, made in front of all thirty companions, means losing involves communal shame. The <strong>linen garments</strong> (<em>sĕdînîm</em>, H5466) were a luxury item imported from Egypt or Phoenicia; 'changes of clothing' (<em>ḥălîpôt bĕgādîm</em>) were formal dress sets for different occasions, not everyday work clothing.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The riddle — <strong>'Out of the eater came food; out of the strong came sweetness'</strong> — is structurally insoluble without knowing the lion-honey incident. ANE riddle tradition distinguished between fair riddles (solvable by logic or knowledge the audience possesses) and impossible riddles (requiring inside information). Using an impossible riddle as a wager was considered by some as a form of sharp dealing. The companions' three-day failure (v.14b) establishes that no amount of conventional reasoning can crack it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The escalation from intellectual pressure to <strong>death threat</strong> — 'coax your husband or we will burn you and your father's house with fire' — reflects the honor-violence logic of the ancient world: the 30 men have staked public honor on solving the riddle, and failure means communal shame. Burning someone's house was a recognized instrument of tribal punishment (Judg 12:1; 15:6); the threat is credible. The seven-day duration also puts the bride's family in the impossible position: hospitality requires protecting guests, but the threat endangers their own household.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Samson's wife's accusation — <strong>'You only hate me, you don't love me'</strong> — employs the emotional rhetoric of the ANE domestic sphere. The claim reverses the expected covenant loyalty: she inverts the love-proof demand (if you loved me, you would tell me). The same emotional logic appears in Delilah's successful appeal (16:15). This is the first demonstration of a pattern in the Samson narrative: women use intimate relationship as leverage to extract covenant secrets from him.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The seven days of weeping correspond exactly to the seven-day feast — the pressure is maintained for the entire duration. <strong>'Because she pressed him hard'</strong> (<em>kî ṣārĕrāh-lô</em>, she was a narrow/pressing-place to him) — the verb ṣārar means to be in straits, to be hemmed in; she made his situation feel desperate. The social and emotional pressure of the feast context — surrounded by Philistine companions, unable to avoid his wife's weeping, in enemy territory — explains why Samson breaks where he does.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The companions' answer — <strong>'What is sweeter than honey? What is stronger than a lion?'</strong> — technically answers the riddle by giving natural referents, but Samson recognizes it as derived knowledge. His response ('if you had not plowed with my heifer') uses agricultural metaphor: <em>ʿeglāh</em> (H5697, heifer) refers to his wife, and <em>ḥaraštEM</em> (plowed) refers to sexual/intimate access. The agricultural idiom for sexual knowledge is common in the ANE (Song 4:12-16 uses garden imagery similarly). The deadline 'before the sun set' confirms the legal precision of the wager: sunset ended the seventh day.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>Ashkelon</strong> was one of the five Philistine city-states (the Pentapolis: Gaza, Ashkelon, Ashdod, Ekron, Gath), located on the Mediterranean coast about 38 km southwest of Timnah. It was a major port and commercial center, with a dense population. The Spirit of YHWH empowers Samson to kill thirty Ashkelonites — strangers entirely unconnected to the riddle dispute — to pay the wager. The moral problem this raises is left unaddressed by the narrator: the Spirit-empowerment is noted without editorial comment. Samson takes the garments and pays the debt, then departs 'in anger' (<em>ḥărî ʾappô</em>, burning of his nostrils).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The bride given to the companion (<em>mērēaʿ</em>, best man or closest companion) was legally possible in the ANE when a husband abandoned his wife without formal divorce. The Hammurabi Code (§137-138) and other ANE legal texts address the question of abandoned wives; remarriage to another man was recognized after a period of abandonment. From the Philistine father's perspective, Samson left without consummating the marriage publicly and without formal divorce, making the transfer legally reasonable. For Samson, this represents a double betrayal: his wife betrayed his secret, and the Philistines gave her away.</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>The <strong>wheat harvest</strong> (<em>qĕṣîr ḥiṭṭîm</em>) places this episode in late spring, roughly May-June — about the time of the feast of Weeks (Shavuot, Pentecost). Samson's visit with a <strong>young goat</strong> (<em>gĕdî ʿizzîm</em>) as a gift follows ANE custom for reconciliation visits or visits to a spouse after an estrangement. The same gift-gesture appears in Judg 6:19 (Gideon to the angel) and Gen 38:17 (Judah to Tamar). Bringing a goat to 'go in to his wife' uses the standard Hebrew euphemism for sexual relations.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Her father's explanation — <strong>'I was sure you utterly hated her'</strong> (<em>śānōʾ śĕnēʾtāh</em>, the infinitive absolute for emphasis) — invokes the legal concept of divorce by abandonment. ANE marriage contracts typically specified that a husband who deserted his wife without support or divorce proceedings forfeited his rights. The father's offer of the younger sister as a replacement reflects the ANE practice of levirate-adjacent arrangements where family honor required providing the man with a wife. 'Isn't her younger sister more beautiful?' appeals to practical resolution.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Samson's declaration of <strong>blamelessness</strong> — <em>niqqêtî</em> (H5352, I am clean/innocent) — is a forensic term from covenant law. He is establishing that his subsequent action is legally justified retaliation, not unprovoked aggression. In the honor-shame culture of the ancient world, the sequence of offense (wife given away) → declaration of clean hands → proportional response was a recognized social script. The Philistines' action against him (via his wife) justifies his action against them.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The capture of <strong>300 foxes</strong> (or jackals — the Hebrew <em>šûʿālîm</em> refers to both species) is the most discussed logistical element of the Samson narrative. Using animals to destroy crops was a recognized form of agricultural warfare: Song 2:15 mentions foxes that destroy vineyards. The pairing of animals with firebrands and releasing them into grain fields exploits the animals' natural tendency to flee into cover (agricultural fields) when frightened. The scale (300 animals, paired in 150 pairs) is likely hyperbolic — the point is total destruction of the Philistine harvest, not a precise census of foxes.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The targets — <strong>standing grain, shocks of grain, and olive orchards</strong> — represent the complete agricultural wealth of a settlement. Standing grain was the unharvested crop; shocks were already cut and stacked for threshing; the orchards were the long-term capital investment (olive trees take 15-20 years to mature). Destroying all three meant the community would face both immediate hunger and multi-year agricultural recovery. This is total economic warfare, calibrated to inflict maximum long-term damage.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Philistines' response — burning the Timnite woman and her father — is collective punishment, the standard ANE mechanism for penalizing a family for an offense committed by one of its members. They identify Samson's motive correctly (he was wronged by his wife's remarriage) and execute the offending family. This creates the next cycle: the Philistines kill the woman to punish Samson, who then attacks the Philistines again in retaliation. The narrative structure shows an escalating reciprocal honor-violence cycle characteristic of ANE tribal warfare.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samson's vow — <strong>'If this is what you do, I will certainly take revenge'</strong> — uses the oath formula 'im-lōʾ... ʿim' (surely/if-not). Revenge (<em>nāqam</em>, H5358) in the ancient world was not understood primarily as emotional retaliation but as the restoration of broken social order: when someone harmed you without justification, you had both the right and the social obligation to restore the honor balance. Samson's 'and after that I will stop' suggests he envisions a final reckoning, not ongoing warfare.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'<strong>Hip and thigh</strong>' (<em>šôq ʿal-yārēk</em>) is a Hebrew idiom for thoroughness or severity in battle; the literal meaning (thigh upon hip) may describe a specific killing technique — pinning or disabling — but the phrase's idiomatic sense is 'a great and complete slaughter.' The retreat to the <strong>cave at Etam</strong> (identified in 2 Chr 11:6 as a fortified town in the Shephelah of Judah) shows Samson withdrawing to Judahite territory after his raid — seeking sanctuary within his own people's borders.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>Lehi</strong> (H3896, jaw/jawbone — the name is aetiological, given after the battle described in vv.15-17) was in the Shephelah, roughly in the territory of Judah near the border with the Philistines. The Philistine military expedition into Judah (<em>wayyaʿălû pĕlištîm</em>, they came up) shows that Samson's actions have triggered a full-scale military response: a single individual's guerrilla warfare has provoked an army-level incursion, demonstrating Samson's strategic significance to both sides.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Judahites' question — 'why have you come up against us?' — and the Philistine answer — 'to bind Samson and do to him as he did to us' — frames this as a law-enforcement operation, not an invasion. The Philistines present themselves as seeking proportional justice, using legal language (<em>kaʾăšer ʿāśāh lānû</em>, as he did to us). The Judahites' response (going to bind Samson themselves, vv.11-12) shows how deeply they have accepted Philistine overlordship: they are willing to deliver their own deliverer to avoid conflict with their occupiers.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'<strong>Don't you know that the Philistines rule over us?</strong>' (<em>lōʾ yādaʿtā kî mōšĕlîm bānû pĕlištîm</em>) — the question reveals the depth of Judah's accommodation to foreign domination. By the period of Samson, Philistine domination had been normalized to the point where the tribe of Judah regarded a deliverer as a threat to social stability rather than a gift. This is precisely the spiritual condition that the Deuteronomic cycle diagnoses: when Israel stops crying out to YHWH (as they apparently do in the Samson narrative — no corporate cry of distress precedes his birth), they lose their freedom and eventually their desire for it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The social prohibition against killing a member of your own people — <strong>'We will only bind you and hand you over'</strong> — reflects the ANE tribal law of blood-covenant: shedding the blood of your own kinsman was a categorical violation that would create a blood-feud within Judah itself. The 3,000 men of Judah who come to bind Samson are acting within recognized social-legal constraints. Samson's one condition ('swear you won't kill me yourselves') accepts the binding in exchange for the guarantee against intra-tribal bloodshed.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The <strong>two new ropes</strong> (<em>ḥăbālîm ḥădāšîm šĕnayim</em>) are a symbol of the strongest ordinary restraint available. In ANE and later contexts, 'new' ropes or bonds that have never been used were considered to have maximum strength (not weakened by use). The same logic appears in Samson's later deceptions with Delilah: the tests use 'unused' or 'fresh' binding materials. The ropes of Judah, representing human effort to contain divine power, will prove no more effective than the ropes Delilah uses.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Philistines' war cry (<em>yĕrûʿû liqrāʾtô</em>, shouted against him) as Samson arrives was an ANE intimidation technique — battle cries were used to frighten enemies before combat. The Spirit of YHWH rushing upon Samson at this moment (the same formula as 13:25, 14:6, 14:19) transforms the Judahites' ropes into burnt flax — the contrast of fire imagery (Samson's weakness becoming as fire-consumed flax) with the fire of the foxes episode creates a recurring fire motif in the Samson cycle.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A <strong>fresh jawbone of a donkey</strong> (<em>lĕḥî ḥămôr ṭərîyyāh</em>) — the qualifier 'fresh' (<em>ṭārî</em>, H2961, moist/new) is practically significant: a dried jawbone would be brittle, while a fresh one retains its density and durability. Donkey jawbones are substantial — the lower mandible of a mature donkey weighs about 0.5 kg with a natural grip in the skull socket. As an improvised weapon, it functioned as a club/chopper rather than a blade. The weapon's choice reflects Samson's characteristic improvisation — he fights with what is at hand.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Samson's victory song (<em>ḥămôr ḥămōr ātayim biḥlĕqat haḥămôr hikkêtî ʾelep ʾîš</em>) is an untranslatable pun: <em>ḥămôr</em> means both 'donkey' and (possibly) 'heap,' while <em>ḥămōr ātayim</em> means 'two heaps/a donkey's heap.' The song celebrates the victory through wordplay, a common form of Hebrew victory poetry (cf. Deborah's song, ch.5; Moses' song, Exod 15). Short victory songs (<em>šîrê qĕṣer</em>) were a standard form of ANE military commemoration, often tied to specific weapons or tactics.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>Ramath-lehi</strong> (Height of the Jawbone) is an aetiological place-name created at the moment of victory. Place-name etiologies — where a place receives its name from a specific event — are a narrative device throughout Judges and Genesis: Beer-lahai-roi (Gen 16:14), Mahanaim (Gen 32:2), Penuel (Gen 32:30), Beer (Judg 9:21). The jawbone's throwing away (<em>wayyašlēk</em>) marks the weapon as ritually significant — Samson discards it rather than keeping it as a trophy, perhaps recognizing it as a dead-animal object requiring disposal.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samson's prayer — <strong>'You have given this great deliverance by the hand of your servant'</strong> — is his first direct prayer in the narrative and uses formal covenant-address language: <em>ʿaḇdekā</em> (your servant) positions him as YHWH's vassal. The theological acknowledgment is followed immediately by existential crisis: extreme thirst after extraordinary physical exertion. The prayer's pattern (acknowledgment of divine action + personal need) mirrors many Psalms of thanksgiving (Ps 118:5-6: 'In my distress I called on YHWH... YHWH is on my side; I will not fear').</p>",
    "19": "<p>The water miracle — <strong>God split open the hollow place (<em>makteš</em>, H4388, mortar/hollow) in Lehi</strong> — parallels Exod 17:6 (water from the rock at Meribah) and Num 20:8-11 (Kadesh). The spring is named <strong>En-hakkore</strong> (H5875, Spring of the One Who Cries Out/the Caller) — aetiological again, the place named for Samson's prayer. The water miracle's location at the place of the jawbone victory links the two events: where Samson won by the Spirit's power, he is also sustained by God's provision. The name En-hakkore 'is in Lehi to this day' — an archival note authenticating the tradition.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samson's <strong>twenty-year judgeship</strong> — the only tenure length given in the Samson narrative — is notably characterized as being 'in the days of the Philistines' rather than resulting in 'rest' (<em>šāqaṭ</em>, the standard Judges formula). Every other major judge gives the land rest (3:11, 3:30, 5:31, 8:28); Samson does not. His deliverance is partial and personal, not communal and complete. The Philistine domination continues through his entire tenure and beyond — his death in ch.16 does not produce liberation. This is the narrator's assessment of the Samson period: a deliverer who delivers himself more than his people.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p><strong>Gaza</strong> was the southernmost and most militarily powerful of the five Philistine city-states, located about 80 km southwest of Zorah. For Samson to enter Gaza alone was an act of extreme provocation — the Philistines' capital-level stronghold, deep in enemy territory. The <strong>prostitute</strong> (<em>ʾiššāh zônāh</em>) — the same phrase used for Rahab (Josh 2:1) — was a recognized professional in ANE cities, often operating near city gates. Samson's visit to a prostitute in Gaza is presented without comment: the narrator has long since stopped evaluating his personal choices, letting the consequences speak.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The <strong>city gate</strong> of an ANE city was both its primary defense point and its administrative center — courts met there, commerce was transacted there, and its physical structure was the city's embodiment of power. Gates were locked from sunset to sunrise (cf. Josh 2:5 — Jericho's gate was shut when the spies arrived at night). The Gazites' plan — surround Samson, set an ambush, and kill him at dawn when the gate opened — was militarily sensible: the gate opening was the one predictable moment when Samson must pass through a chokepoint. They kept themselves quiet all night, not revealing their presence.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Carrying the entire <strong>city gate structure</strong> — doors, posts, and bar — to a hilltop was a symbolic act of extraordinary cultural significance. In ANE thought, the city gate was the city's power and identity: 'possessing the gates of enemies' (Gen 22:17) meant total victory. Carrying Gaza's gate to the hill facing Hebron (approximately 60 km away) publicly humiliated the Philistine city and advertised Samson's invulnerability. The hill facing Hebron was in Judahite territory — Samson is placing Gaza's symbol of power in Israel's central highland, visible to both peoples.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <strong>Valley of Sorek</strong> (Sorek = 'choice vine') is the same valley where Timnah lay — the frontier zone between Philistia and Judah. <strong>Delilah</strong>'s name may derive from <em>dālal</em> (to be low, to hang down) or be related to Aramaic words for night. She is the only woman in the Samson cycle given a personal name, giving her a narrative dignity denied the Timnite and the Gaza prostitute. Her ethnicity is unspecified — she could be Israelite, Philistine, or mixed; the text does not say, which has generated interpretive debate.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The bribe offered by each of the <strong>five lords of the Philistines</strong> (<em>sarnê pĕlištîm</em> — the title <em>seren</em> may relate to Greek <em>tyrannos</em> or an Aegean term for ruler) was <strong>1,100 pieces of silver each</strong>, totaling 5,500 pieces. For comparison: 30 silver pieces was the value of a slave (Exod 21:32); the Levite in ch.17 earns 10 silver per year; 5,500 silver pieces was extraordinary wealth. The five lords acting in concert reflects the Philistine city-state confederation — they operated as a league for major strategic decisions. Their willingness to pay this much shows how seriously they regarded Samson as a military threat.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Delilah's repeated question — <strong>'Tell me where your great strength lies'</strong> — targets the secret of Samson's power. In ANE magical thinking, the source of supernatural power was often believed to be located in a specific object, place, or practice; knowing the source gave access to counter-power. This is why the question is framed in terms of <em>where</em> (location of power) rather than <em>why</em> (covenant relationship). The request to discover how he could be <em>bound</em> and <em>humbled</em> (<em>ʿinnāhû</em>) is simultaneously sexual and military — the same word used for the violation of the Levite's concubine in ch.19.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>Seven fresh bowstrings</strong> (<em>šiḇʿāh yětārîm lēḥîm ʾăšer lōʾ-ḥoraḇû</em>, seven moist bowstrings not dried) — sinew or gut bowstrings retained some elasticity when fresh but became brittle when dried. The number seven has ritual significance in ANE cultures (seven days of creation, seven-day feasts, seven-year cycles); its appearance in Samson's deceptions may reflect folk-magical thinking about the power of specific numbers. The 'not dried' condition suggests Samson is specifying the strongest possible form — if even these cannot hold him, he is invincible.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The <strong>Philistine lords</strong> bring the bowstrings personally (<em>wayyaʿălû-lāh sarnê pĕlištîm</em>) — this is not delegated to servants but handled at the highest level, reflecting the strategic importance of neutralizing Samson. The men lying in wait in the inner room (<em>baḥeder</em>, in the innermost chamber) is a tense domestic-military operation: the ambush is set within a private residence, with Delilah as both agent and decoy.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Delilah's cry — <strong>'The Philistines are upon you!'</strong> — was a scripted alarm. Samson's snapping of the bowstrings 'as a thread of flax breaks when it touches fire' uses the same fire imagery as the Lehi battle: fire consumes what should restrain him. The phrase '<strong>his strength was not known</strong>' at the end of v.9 is crucial: the hidden Philistines watching the test confirm that Delilah's intelligence is worthless. The threefold testing pattern that follows (vv.10-14) establishes the rhythm of deception before the fatal truth.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Delilah's accusation — <strong>'You have mocked me'</strong> (<em>tĕhātēl bî</em>, from <em>hātal</em>, to mock/deceive) — inverts the situation: she is deceiving him for pay, but accuses him of deception. The moral universe of the Samson narrative is consistently inverted: the one being used claims the one doing the using is untrustworthy. Her persistence is the key variable — each failure leads not to disclosure but to re-engagement.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>New ropes that have never been used</strong> (<em>ʿăḇōtîm ḥădāšîm ʾăšer lōʾ-ʿuśśāh ḇāhem mĕlāʾkāh</em>) — the 'new and unused' emphasis mirrors the binding of Samson by Judah (15:13 — new ropes). The repeated use of 'new' bonds in Samson's deceptions reflects the folk belief that used objects carry the history of previous uses, while new objects carry full potential power. That Samson uses this same framework (new = strongest) but gives false information shows he understands the magical thinking involved.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The second test plays out identically to the first: Delilah binds, shouts the alarm, the hidden Philistines are present, Samson breaks free. The narrative repetition is a suspense technique — each repetition raises the question of when and how the pattern will break. In ANE folktale tradition, the third request in a threefold series is the climactic one; here the pattern extends to four, with the fourth being the fatal truth.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The third test involves Samson's <strong>hair woven into fabric</strong> (<em>wayyāʾrag bammasseket</em>, you weave into the web) — Delilah is weaving Samson's head into the loom while he sleeps. The test moves progressively closer to the actual answer: bowstrings → ropes → hair (but woven, not cut). This escalation shows Delilah correctly deducing that the secret involves the hair but misunderstanding the mechanism (cutting versus weaving).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The <strong>pin</strong> (<em>wayyitqaʿ bayāḇēd</em>, fastened with a peg) completes the weaving test: the braid is secured to the loom with a tent-peg. When the alarm is sounded, Samson wakes and pulls free, taking both pin and beam with him — his strength is so superior that he uproots the entire weaving apparatus. The image of the loom-peg and beam dragged away continues the series of 'strongest restraints defeated.'</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>'How can you say you love me when your heart is not with me?'</strong> — Delilah's appeal pivots from testing to emotional coercion. She uses the vocabulary of covenant love (<em>ʾāhaḇtanî</em>) and intimate presence (<em>libbĕkā ʾênnennû ʾittî</em>, your heart is not with me) — the same relational language of Deuteronomy's command to love YHWH with all your heart (Deut 6:5). In the honor-shame social world, a man's failure to share intimate knowledge with his beloved was evidence of contempt, not prudence.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>'She pressed him day after day with her words'</strong> (<em>wayyĕhî kî-hēṣîqāh lô biḏḇārêhā kol-hayyāmîm wattĕʾālāṣēhû</em>) — the repeated verbal pressure over days corresponds to the sustained emotional attrition of the Timnite wife's seven-day weeping (14:17). Samson's soul was <em>qĕṣĕrāh</em> (shortened/wearied to death) — the verb suggests a psychological wearing-down that compromised judgment. Ancient readers would have recognized the pattern: the strong man defeated by persistent emotional pressure rather than military force.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>'A razor has never come upon my head, for I have been a Nazirite to God from my mother's womb'</strong> — the first time Samson explicitly acknowledges his Nazirite status. The Nazirite vow (Num 6:1-21) prohibited three things: wine and fermented drink, contact with corpses, and cutting the hair. Samson has already violated the first two (he attended wine feasts; he touched the lion's carcass). The hair is the last intact external sign of the vow — the visible token of his consecration. His confession that 'if I am shaved, my strength will leave me and I will become weak like any other man' shows he understands the connection between consecration and power.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Delilah's recognition — <strong>'He had told her all his heart'</strong> (<em>kî-higgîd lāh ʾet-kol-libbô</em>) — uses the language of complete self-disclosure: <em>kol-libbô</em>, all his heart. The heart (<em>lēb</em>) in Hebrew anthropology is the seat of thought, will, and commitment — to tell 'all his heart' is to hold nothing back. Delilah's response is immediate: she sends for the lords (plural — the intelligence has military-strategic value), specifying that 'this time' he has told her, distinguishing the genuine revelation from the previous deceptions. The lords' response — bringing their money — confirms the transactional nature of the arrangement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Delilah lulls Samson to sleep on her lap (<em>wayyîšan ʿal-birkêhā</em>) — a position of total vulnerability and trust, the most intimate of postures. She summons a man to shave the seven locks: Delilah herself does not do the shaving, suggesting she is managing the operation rather than executing it. The <strong>seven locks</strong> (<em>šeḇaʿ maḥlĕpôt rōʾšô</em>) correspond to the seven bowstrings of the first deception — the number seven is consistent throughout the Samson-binding motif. 'She began to torment him' (<em>wattoḥel lĕʿannōtô</em>) — the same affliction-root as for the concubine's abuse in 19:25.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>'He did not know that YHWH had departed from him'</strong> (<em>wĕhûʾ lōʾ yādaʿ kî YHWH sār mēʿālāyw</em>) — the most theologically charged verse in the Samson narrative. The identical construction (<em>lōʾ yādaʿ</em>, he did not know) appears at 14:4 (his parents did not know about the lion) and 20:34 (the Benjamites did not know disaster was coming). Here it describes the most tragic ignorance: Samson assumes his power is still available after the covenant sign is gone. The phrase 'as at other times' (<em>kĕpaʿam bĕpaʿam</em>) shows he expected continuity — he had grown accustomed to the Spirit's power without attending to the conditions of consecration.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Philistines' treatment of Samson — <strong>gouging out his eyes</strong>, binding with bronze shackles, forcing him to grind at the mill — reflects documented ANE practices. Blinding defeated kings and dangerous prisoners was a recognized punishment in Assyrian and Egyptian warfare (Zedekiah's blinding, 2 Kgs 25:7; the blinding of rebellious vassals in Assyrian royal inscriptions). Bronze shackles (nĕḥuštayim) were ceremonial as well as practical — displaying a famous captive in bronze was an honor-degradation ritual. Mill-grinding was slave labor, the lowest social status, typically assigned to women (Exod 11:5) or the most despised captives.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>'But the hair of his head began to grow back'</strong> — a transitional verse inserted between Samson's capture and the Dagon festival. The hair's regrowth is significant: the Nazirite vow's external sign is being restored, even though Samson is blind and imprisoned. The text does not comment on whether his strength was returning — the reader is left to wonder until vv.28-30. The hair detail is the narrator's preparation of the reader for the coming denouement: the sign of consecration is visibly present again before the final act.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>Dagon</strong> (H1712) was the chief deity of the Philistine pantheon, associated with grain and fertility in both Ugaritic texts (where he appears as the father of Baal) and Mesopotamian religion. His worship is attested at Ugarit (14th century BCE), at Ebla (24th century BCE), and in the Philistine cities of Gaza and Ashdod (1 Sam 5:2-7). The festival celebrating Samson's capture was a standard ANE victory-thanksgiving: military victories were attributed to divine patronage, and captured enemies were displayed as trophies of the god's power. The lords assembled, the whole Philistine ruling class, making this a state religious ceremony.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Philistine celebration chant — <strong>'Our god has given our enemy into our hand'</strong> — mirrors the exact language Israel used to celebrate YHWH's victories (Judg 11:32: 'YHWH gave them into his hand'; Josh 6:2: 'I have given Jericho into your hand'). The irony is intentional: the same theological grammar of divine warfare is being used by both sides. The narrator is not relativizing — Dagon is an idol — but showing that even pagan worship recognizes the framework of divinely-granted victory. Their identification of Samson as 'the one who devastated our land' shows they correctly assessed his strategic impact.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Displaying captives for entertainment was common in ANE royal court and temple culture. The verb <em>yĕśaḥeq</em> (perform/play before us) can mean both entertainment-performance and more degrading displays; the same root appears in the 'playing' before the Ark that David does (2 Sam 6:21). 'He was positioned between the pillars' — the placement is both theatrical (center stage for display) and architecturally significant. The crowd's 'merry hearts' (<em>kî-ṭôḇ libbām</em>) contrast with Samson's 'wearing down to death' (<em>qĕṣĕrāh napšô</em>) in v.16: joy at the expense of the humiliated captive.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Samson's request to 'feel the pillars' is addressed to his attendant (<em>hannaar hammahazîq bĕyādô</em>, the young man holding his hand) — Samson is completely dependent on a guide. The image of the once-invincible hero being led by hand to his place of entertainment is the fullest expression of his degradation. His request to lean against the pillars (<em>lāšaʿăn ʿălêhem</em>, to rest/lean on them) is presented as a practical request; the young man's placement between the pillars (v.29) shows the request is granted without suspicion.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The description of the temple's capacity — <strong>'about 3,000 men and women on the roof watching'</strong> — has been corroborated by archaeology. The Philistine temple excavated at <strong>Tel Qasile</strong> (Stratum X-XI, 11th-10th century BCE) shows a rectangular hall supported by two central wooden pillars on stone bases approximately 2 meters apart, with a total capacity of several hundred inside and more on the roof. A larger version of this pillared-hall design could accommodate the numbers described. The architectural detail — two central columns bearing the roof load — is specific and consistent with excavated Philistine temple architecture.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Samson's prayer — <strong>'O Lord YHWH, remember me please and strengthen me this one time'</strong> (<em>ʾăḏōnāy YHWH zākrēnî nā wĕḥazzĕqēnî nā ʾak happáʿam hazzeh</em>) — is his fullest and most theologically significant address to YHWH. The double divine title (Adonai + YHWH) appears in covenant-intimacy contexts (Deut 3:24; Ps 71:5; Ezek 2:4). <em>Zākrēnî</em> (remember me) is the same prayer of the psalmist in desperate situations (Ps 25:7; 106:4; Luke 23:42). His motive — 'that I may be avenged on the Philistines for my two eyes' — is personal rather than covenantal, yet YHWH answers the prayer, showing grace to the flawed Nazirite.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The architectural action — <strong>grasping the two middle pillars and bracing against them</strong> — is precisely described: right hand on one pillar, left hand on the other, leaning his weight against both simultaneously. The physics of a pillared-hall structure: if the two central load-bearing columns are pushed outward simultaneously, the roof collapses inward. This is the structural vulnerability of the pillared-hall design. The action requires both hands occupied (no weapon) and maximum body leverage — the final expression of Samson's physical power, appropriately applied not to a conventional enemy but to the architectural system that the enemy trusted.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'<strong>Let me die with the Philistines</strong>' (<em>tāmōt napšî ʿim-pĕlištîm</em>) — Samson's words are his only recorded prayer for death; Hebrew Scriptures have few such prayers (Elijah: 1 Kgs 19:4; Jonah: 4:3; Job: 3:11). The final push topples the temple. The narrator's summary: <em>wĕhammētîm ʾăšer hēmît bĕmôtô rabbû mēʾăšer hēmît bĕḥayyāyw</em> (the dead whom he killed in his dying were more than those he killed in his life) — the same principle of death producing more fruit than life, which Jesus applies in John 12:24.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Samson's burial <strong>'between Zorah and Eshtaol'</strong> — these two towns appear at the beginning of the Samson narrative (13:25: 'the Spirit began to stir him between Zorah and Eshtaol'). His story closes geographically where it began: he returns in death to the territory where YHWH first moved in him. His brothers and father's household collect his body from the rubble — the family's retrieval of the body was a matter of covenant obligation (non-burial was a curse in ANE culture: Jer 22:18-19; Amos 2:1). He judged Israel twenty years — the summary repeats v.20, framing the entire Gaza-Delilah episode as embedded within his judgeship.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>The transition from the Samson cycle to the Judges epilogue (chs. 17-21) is abrupt and disorienting. Chapters 17-21 are widely recognized as a literary appendix inserted out of chronological order — the Phinehas reference in 20:28 places the Gibeah episode early in the period, not at the end. The <strong>hill country of Ephraim</strong> was the central highland of Canaan, Israelite heartland, but as the Micah story shows, geographical centrality did not imply spiritual fidelity. <strong>Micah</strong> (H4321, 'who is like YHWH?') — the name's meaning is ironic given the narrative content.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The eleven hundred silver pieces (<em>ʾelep ûmēʾāh kesep</em>) links this episode to the Delilah narrative (16:5 — each Philistine lord offered 1,100 pieces): either the amount is conventional for large bribes, or the narrator is making an intertextual connection. The mother's <strong>oath-curse</strong> (<em>ʾāmôr qillaltā</em>, you uttered a curse) concerning the stolen silver illustrates the practical power of spoken curses in the ancient world — Micah feared the curse's effect and confessed to remove it. ANE curse-law: a spoken curse upon a thief, if the thief was listening, could have automatic effect.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The mother's dedication — <strong>'I consecrate the silver to YHWH for my son to make a carved image and a cast idol'</strong> (<em>haqḏēš hiqdašti ʾet-hakkesef laYHWH miyyāḏî liḇnî laʿăśôt pesel ûmassēkāh</em>) — is a remarkable contradiction: she uses YHWH's name to consecrate an object the Decalogue explicitly forbids (Exod 20:4-5; Deut 5:8-9). This is syncretism in its most direct form — the idol is made with covenant vocabulary. The combination of <em>pesel</em> (carved image) and <em>massēkāh</em> (cast idol) covers both sculptural techniques, suggesting a composite object.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The <strong>silversmith</strong> (<em>ṣôrep</em>, H6884, a refiner/metalworker) is commissioned to make the idol from 200 of the 1,100 pieces — the remainder going elsewhere (not explained). The two hundred are 'given to the silversmith,' a professional craftsman whose specialized skills were in demand throughout the ANE. The production of divine images was a specialized trade in the ancient world, surrounded by ritual protocols (Babylonian <em>mīs pî</em>, 'mouth-washing' ceremony, was performed on newly crafted idols to animate them). Micah's idol is made by craft, contradicting YHWH's self-revelation through history and word.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Micah's <strong>house of God</strong> (<em>bêt ʾĕlōhîm</em>) is a private shrine — the same term used for legitimate sanctuary sites (Gen 28:17; Judg 20:18), here applied to a domestic idol-house. The <strong>ephod</strong> (<em>ʾēpôd</em>, H646) was a priestly garment associated with divination and oracular inquiry (1 Sam 23:9-12; 30:7-8); its presence at an unofficial shrine suggests Micah wanted access to divine guidance outside the legitimate Tabernacle system. <strong>Teraphim</strong> (<em>tĕrāpîm</em>, H8655) were household idols used for divination — Rachel stole Laban's teraphim (Gen 31:19); they were consulted for oracles (Ezek 21:21; Zech 10:2). Micah installs his own son as priest: only Levites (and specifically Aaronide descendants) were authorized as priests (Num 3:10).</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>'In those days there was no king in Israel; each person did what was right in his own eyes'</strong> (<em>bayyāmîm hāhēm ʾên melek bĕyiśrāʾēl ʾîš hayyāšār bĕʿênāyw yaʿăśeh</em>) — the first appearance of the book's closing refrain in its full form. The narrator uses it not at the end but as a caption for the Micah episode: this is why the idolatry happened. <em>ʾên melek</em> (no king) implies not merely the absence of political authority but of the covenant king — Deuteronomy 17:18-20 mandated a king who would read and obey the Torah, ensuring that his reign anchored the community's covenant fidelity. Without such a king, private judgment replaces covenant law.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A <strong>young man from Bethlehem in Judah, from the family of Judah, who was a Levite</strong> — the Levite's introduction is theologically puzzling: how can someone be 'from the family of Judah' (Judahite by birth-mother?) and also a Levite? The most likely explanation is that he was born of a Judahite mother and a Levite father, or that he lived as a sojourner within Judah's territory (as Levites typically did — they had no tribal land, Deut 18:1-8). Levites were the designated teachers and sanctuary personnel; a Levite sojourning without a place of service was economically vulnerable, dependent on the tithe-system and hospitality of other tribes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Levite is <strong>seeking a suitable place</strong> (<em>lagûr baʾăšer yimṣāʾ</em>, to sojourn wherever he could find it) — a phrase that captures the economic precarity of Levites outside the covenant structure. Deuteronomy repeatedly commands care for Levites, strangers, widows, and orphans (Deut 14:29; 16:11, 14; 26:12-13) because they had no land-inheritance. When the covenant community stops supporting Levites, the Levites must find patrons. His arrival 'in the hill country of Ephraim, to Micah's house' suggests aimless wandering brought him to the one person who needed what he could offer.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Levite identifies himself: <strong>'I am a Levite from Bethlehem in Judah, and I am looking for a place to stay.'</strong> His self-identification as a Levite is a professional credential — Levites were the authorized handlers of sacred objects and the legitimate candidates for priestly service. Micah immediately recognizes the commercial value of this credential: having a real Levite is better than having his own son as priest (v.5). The transaction is about to be negotiated on purely economic terms, showing the commodification of the priesthood.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Micah's offer — <strong>'Be my father and priest'</strong> (<em>heyeh-lî lĕʾāḇ ûlĕkōhēn</em>) — uses 'father' as an honorific title of seniority and spiritual authority, not biological relationship. In patronage relationships of the ANE, calling a dependent advisor 'father' elevated his status while acknowledging the client's dependence on his expertise. The annual wage — <strong>ten pieces of silver, a suit of clothes, and food</strong> (<em>ʿăśeret kesep layyāmîm wĕʾereḵ bĕgādîm ûmîḥyātek</em>) — was a modest household income. For comparison, Ruth and Naomi's precarious subsistence gleaning shows how low the survival threshold was; ten silver per year was not wealth but stability.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Levite's agreement (<em>wayyôʾel hallēwî lāšeḇet ʾet-hāʾîš</em>, the Levite consented to stay) uses the same verb <em>yāʾal</em> (to agree/be willing) used for Ruth's decision to stay with Naomi (Ruth 1:14, <em>wayyôʾel Rût</em>). The comparison highlights the contrast: Ruth's loyalty is covenantal and redemptive; the Levite's agreement is economic and ultimately corrupting. 'He became to him like one of his sons' — the patron-client relationship that replaces the covenant community as the Levite's social anchor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Micah <strong>ordained</strong> the Levite (<em>waymallēʾ Mîkāh ʾet-yad hallēwî</em>, Micah filled the hand of the Levite) — the idiom for priestly ordination appears throughout Exodus and Leviticus for Aaron's ordination (Exod 28:41; 29:9; Lev 8:33). It means to formally install in office, often with a gift 'placed in the hands.' Micah performs what only YHWH could authorize through the Mosaic constitution — he ordains a priest outside the established covenant order. The Levite 'was like one of his sons' and also 'became his priest': the dual relationship — quasi-familial and professional — describes the patron-client bond at its most complete.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Micah's confident statement — <strong>'Now I know that YHWH will do good to me, for I have a Levite as my priest'</strong> — is the chapter's theological punchline. His logic: Levite = legitimate priestly credential = guaranteed blessing from YHWH. This is religious instrumentalism: covenant relationship reduced to the correct institutional personnel. The assumption that YHWH's blessing can be secured by managing the right religious apparatus, regardless of whether the worship itself conforms to YHWH's revealed will, is the precise error the prophets will later denounce (Isa 1:11-15; Jer 7:1-15; Amos 5:21-24). Micah thinks he has solved the divine-blessing problem by acquiring the right professional.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(existing, JUDGES)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'judges', existing)

    import json as _j
    il = _j.load(open(ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / 'judges.json'))
    all_ok = True
    for ch in [14, 15, 16, 17]:
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys()) - set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(existing.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present ✓')
    chs = sorted(existing.keys(), key=int)
    print(f'Judges mkt-context chapters now: {chs} ({len(chs)}/21)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
